characteristics.participants:
43 neonates with neonatal respiratory distress syndrome
Inclusion criteria


Meeting specific criteria for neonatal respiratory distress syndrome: 

Presents with breathing problems at birth that progressively worsen, flaring nostrils, rapid breathing, grunting sounds when breathing, and chest retractions and cyanosis;

RDS based on chest x‐ray, with grade I and II RDS classified as mild, and grades III and IV RDS classified as severe;

Arterial oxygen partial pressure/fraction of inspiration O2(PaO2/FiO2) ratio of < 300 (PaO2< 60 mm Hg);

Born before 36 weeks of gestation;

Required respiratory support and received 1 dose of surfactant regardless of exposure to antenatal corticosteroids.

Exclusion criteria


Infection from 6 hours to 3 days (defined as white blood cells ≥ 30 x 10^9 ; C‐reactive protein ≥ 3 mg/L within 6 hours, or C‐reactive protein ≥ 5 mg/L within 6–12 hours);

Anaemia (neonatal venous blood ≤ 130 g/L within 2 weeks);

Dyspnoea caused by pulmonary haemorrhage;

Congenital malformations, including PDA (ductus arteriosus was still not closed 72 hours after birth by bedside ultrasound examination, and the left‐to‐right shunt flow was more than 50%);

Heart failure;

Unsmooth crying and heart rate < 100 beats/minute, initial resuscitation management was given, and T‐Piece positive pressure ventilation.

characteristics.interventions:
Infants, while on NIV, were given 200 mg/kg of surfactant (Poractant Alfa) via thin catheter prior to being randomly divided into 2 groups:
Non‐invasive high frequency oscillatory ventilation (nHFOV) (n = 22)


NHFV ventilator (SLEbaby 5000; SLE Limited, South Croydon Surrey, UK);

Amplitude 2–3 times the value for MAP;

MAP 6 –12 cm H2O;

Frequency 6–12 Hz;

FiO20.30 –0.40;

Criteria for stopping nHFOV: (switch to nasal cannula oxygen therapy if required) 

MAP < 6 cm H2O;

FiO2< 0.3;

SpO2> 90%.

Duo positive airway pressure (DuoPAP; Bilevel positive airway pressure) (n = 21)


Using DuoPAP (ACUTRONIC Medical Systems AG, Hirzel, Zurich, Switzerland);

FiO20.3–0.4 cm H2O;

PEEP 5 cm H2O;

PIP 12–15 cm H2O;

Inspiratory time 0.5 sec;

Respiratory rate 30–40 breaths/minute;

Criteria for stopping DuoPAP: 

FiO2< 0.3;

PEEP ≤ 3 cm H2O;

PIP ≤ 5 cm H2O without respiratory distress;

SpO2> 90%;

No abnormalities on blood gas analysis.

The nasal interface was not specified for both groups.

characteristics.outcomes:
Primary outcomes


PaO2;

PaCO2;

OI at 12 and 24 hours after the start of NIV.

Secondary outcomes


The incidences of IVH, PVL, NEC, BPD, and apnoea during the first 72 hours;

Duration of NIV;

Duration of nasal cannula oxygen therapy;

Length of hospital stay;

Time to full feeding.
